<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-248-506  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 248 506.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Telephony  March 12 1990 v218 n11 p32(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>MFS seeks local loop competition. (Metropolitan Fiber Systems Inc.andO;seeks to open local exchanges to more competition)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Mason, Charles.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The president of Metropolitan Fiber Systems Inc (MFS) , Anthony J.andO;Pompliano, seeks to open local telephone exchange to increasedcompetition.andP;  Pompliano feels that greater competition will offerincreased choices and a decrease in prices.andP;  He also feels thatdestroying the local access bottleneck, controlled by telephonecompanies, will increase network usage and ultimately benefitlocal exchange companies (LECs).andP;  Pompliano, however, does notthink LECs want to open their markets to the competition.andP;  MFSwants the Federal Communications Commission (FCC) to maketelephone companies allow alternative access companies to placetheir equipment in existing central offices.andP;  The company alsowants Bell regional holding companies to divide charges for localaccess into component parts.andP;  If MFS wins permission to collocateequipment, it could provide service to customers not on theirfiber optic network.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Metropolitan Fiber Systems Inc. (marketing).andO;Topic:     Telephone companiesUnited States. Federal Communications CommissionRegulationCompetitionMarketing StrategyPlanning.andO;Person:    Pompliano, Anthony J. (aims and objectives).andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>